<div id="review_968311935" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/968311935" />
    <a title="Debra " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5032725-debra"><img alt="Debra " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627589236p2/5032725.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/968311935?book_show_action=true">Jun 15, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Debra " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Debra " href="/user/show/5032725-debra">Debra </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer968311935" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11872543746573948208">Well, I think it is easy to assume that I wont be running out and purchasing a movie ticket to see the movie based on this book. I had to force myself to keep reading this. I didn&apos;t actually like this book until page 85 and I did like the part slightly farther along where Penny finds out that Martin left her to &quot;see his friends&quot; when he really left to go jump off a building was funny in a sad sort of way. Suicide is not a laughing matter. I actually witnessed someone jump to his death so sorry, </span>
  <span id="freeText11872543746573948208" style="display:none">Well, I think it is easy to assume that I wont be running out and purchasing a movie ticket to see the movie based on this book. I had to force myself to keep reading this. I didn't actually like this book until page 85 and I did like the part slightly farther along where Penny finds out that Martin left her to "see his friends" when he really left to go jump off a building was funny in a sad sort of way. Suicide is not a laughing matter. I actually witnessed someone jump to his death so sorry, but I don't' find this to be funny. Having said that, the premise of this was interesting. Four strangers come together on New Years Eve. They have nothing in common except they all want to commit suicide by jumping off a building. We watch them fight, bond, lose a job, save a job, then lose a job again, laugh, fight some more, and in the end they *spoilers* form a pact to rethink suicide in 6 months. Blah. How about seek some mental health treatment instead? Yes, I know this is a book and yes, there were some clever bits. But not clever enough. My husband and half his family are from England so I do get British humor but this book just fell flat for me (no pun intended). Also, I didn't really care for any of the characters. This was my first Hornby book and I do believe it will be my last.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11872543746573948208" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


