    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1733864037" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1733864037" />
    <a title="Ramsey Hootman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5516415-ramsey-hootman"><img alt="Ramsey Hootman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442648237p2/5516415.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1733864037?book_show_action=true">Aug 20, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ramsey Hootman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ramsey Hootman" href="/user/show/5516415-ramsey-hootman">Ramsey Hootman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1733864037" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer950072046889907680">You know how there are books that you know you&apos;d love if you didn&apos;t know so much about a certain topic? Because the author clearly didn&apos;t bother do his or her research, and because you happen to know a lot about the topic, all of the glaring holes basically ruin the entire narrative for you? This is one of those. I hate that it was, because I loved About a Boy and I think Nick Hornby is fantastically funny. And yet. <br/><br/>The premise here is that four people encounter each other on the top of a buildi</span>
  <span id="freeText950072046889907680" style="display:none">You know how there are books that you know you'd love if you didn't know so much about a certain topic? Because the author clearly didn't bother do his or her research, and because you happen to know a lot about the topic, all of the glaring holes basically ruin the entire narrative for you? This is one of those. I hate that it was, because I loved About a Boy and I think Nick Hornby is fantastically funny. And yet. <br /><br />The premise here is that four people encounter each other on the top of a building on New Year's Eve, all planning to commit suicide. They all come to know one another and (sort of) help each other in a variety of unexpected ways. All of the characters agree that the individual with the most legitimate reason for offing herself is the fifty-something mother of a profoundly disabled son. And that's where it falls apart.<br /><br />I was not at all surprised by the way the characters refer to Matty, the now-adult son who is described as nothing more than a "vegetable." Hornby's trademark is profoundly flawed characters, which is something that I love about his writing. However, I assumed that as the book went on, we would get flashes of humanity here and there for Matty, as we see with all the other characters. That was absolutely not the case. As the narrative went on and he remained nothing more than an object, a prop, I became more and more uncomfortable, and began to feel that this was not simply the point of view of the characters, but of the author as well. It began to feel as if the author did not even see Matty as human. <br /><br />What really got me, though, was just the profound lack of accuracy about people with these kinds of disabilities. Let's just review the setup. Maureen, the mother, has been doing nothing but caring for her son Matty since he was born. She is incredibly isolated because she cares for him alone. He does not appear to have any medical problems, he just "exists." She's not wealthy, but occasionally she pays to leave him at a care place. So, her problem, as presented in the book, is her profound isolation. At the end it's solved by her getting to know a couple of nurses from the care facility, leaving Matty more often, and getting a part-time job.<br /><br />But honestly, this setup just isn't even possible. It doesn't even work in the book. Even though she supposedly cares for Matty round the clock, she goes to church on a weekly basis. And her friends at church mostly do not know about Matty. So... how does that work? Where is Matty then? Matty is also described as being tall and definitely adult (19, I think), so how on earth could Maureen possibly care for him by herself? How would this small woman manage to transfer him from his wheelchair to his bed? (I should note that in the narrative, he is always just 'in his chair,' as if he resides here permanently.) He is described as being basically unresponsive in every way, no movement whatsoever. There's no detail about whether his eyes open, if he can swallow on his own, or what. But either way, it doesn't work out. If he's essentially comatose, there is no way Maureen would be able to take care of him by herself, and no way he wouldn't have frequent medical issues that would require professional care and hospitalization. Is he eating through a tube? Does he have a stoma? If he can't shift his own weight, what about bedsores? Bone density loss? Accidental broken bones? There's just no way that Maureen would be stuck at home as his only carer, alone. Or maybe he's not THAT disabled. Maybe he can eat, maybe he can shift, maybe he can move a bit? In which case, the author has done Matty a profound disservice by erasing his character. Even a non-verbal person is capable of having a personality, but Matty is very specifically denied that. He is not a person, he is a prop.<br /><br />In the end, Maureen "learns" that leaving Matty in the care of strangers is okay-- and here's the kicker-- not because she needs to take care of herself first, but because she realizes there's literally no difference between her level of care and that at an institution. Anyone who knows a family with a severely disabled child can tell you this isn't even remotely true. And it's not just a delusion of family members who want to believe that they can make a difference. It's demonstrably better, both emotionally and medically, for a child to be cared for by someone who loves them, knows their body and medical conditions inside out, and can best judge what they need. So much so that where I live (California) parents are paid to be caregivers so that their children can stay out of institutionalized care.<br /><br />Basically, the Maureen/Matty narrative reads like someone's very ignorant assumption of what life must be like for a profoundly disabled person and his carer. It is a "worst-case" scenario that literally does not and could not exist. This is ignorant, and it perpetuates harmful stereotypes about people with disabilities.</span>
  <a data-text-id="950072046889907680" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

